Introduction

Decentralized lending protocols are one of the core primitives of DeFi.
They allow users to:

Deposit assets to earn interest

Borrow assets using collateral

Repay loans

Liquidate unhealthy positions

One of the most influential implementations is Compound V2, which pioneered algorithmic interest rates and over-collateralized lending.

This article explains the core architecture of a decentralized lending protocol and how it can be implemented from scratch.

1. Core Components of a Lending Protocol

A typical lending protocol consists of four major modules:

Asset Pool

Interest Rate Model

Risk Engine

Liquidation Mechanism

These components work together to maintain solvency and enable decentralized borrowing.

2. Asset Pool (Liquidity Layer)

The asset pool holds user deposits and provides liquidity for borrowers.

Example structure:

Total Pool Assets
= totalCash + totalBorrows - totalReserves

Where:

totalCash → assets currently in the pool

totalBorrows → assets borrowed by users

totalReserves → protocol reserves

Users deposit assets into the pool and receive interest-bearing tokens (such as cTokens in Compound).

Example:

100 USDC deposited
↓
Receive 5000 cUSDC

These tokens represent a share of the pool.

3. Exchange Rate Mechanism

The value of interest-bearing tokens grows over time.

Formula:

exchangeRate =
(totalCash + totalBorrows - totalReserves)
/
totalSupply

Meaning:

1 cToken = exchangeRate * underlying asset

As borrowers pay interest:

totalBorrows increases
→ exchangeRate increases
→ suppliers earn yield
4. Interest Rate Model

Interest rates are determined algorithmically based on utilization.

Utilization rate:

utilization =
totalBorrows /
(totalCash + totalBorrows)

Borrow rate model:

borrowRate =
baseRate + utilization * multiplier

Where:

baseRate → minimum borrowing interest

multiplier → slope of the interest rate curve

Higher utilization leads to higher borrowing costs, encouraging more deposits and discouraging excessive borrowing.

5. Collateral System

Borrowing requires collateral.

Each asset has a collateral factor:

maxBorrow =
collateralValue * collateralFactor

Example:

Deposit: 1000 USDC
Collateral Factor: 75%

Maximum borrowable value:

750 USD
6. Risk Engine (Liquidity Calculation)

Before any borrow operation, the protocol calculates account liquidity.

Formula:

liquidity =
Σ(collateral_value × collateral_factor)
-
Σ(borrow_value)

Possible outcomes:

Result	Meaning
liquidity > 0	user can borrow more
liquidity = 0	at borrow limit
shortfall > 0	position is liquidatable

This calculation is the core risk management logic.

7. Borrowing Process

Typical borrow flow:

User deposits collateral
↓
User enters market
↓
Protocol calculates liquidity
↓
Borrow is allowed if collateral is sufficient
↓
Assets are transferred to borrower

Borrowing is always over-collateralized to protect the protocol.

8. Repayment

Repaying loans reduces the borrow balance.

borrowBalance -= repayAmount
totalBorrows -= repayAmount

Interest accrues over time, so the repayment amount includes both principal and interest.

9. Liquidation Mechanism

If collateral value drops and the position becomes undercollateralized:

borrow_value > collateral_value × liquidation_threshold

The position can be liquidated.

Liquidators:

Repay part of the borrower’s debt

Receive collateral at a discount

Example:

Repay: 100 USDC
Receive: 110 USDC worth of collateral

This creates an incentive for liquidators to maintain system solvency.

10. Key Security Risks

Lending protocols must defend against several attack vectors:

Price Oracle Manipulation

If collateral prices rely on manipulable sources (such as AMM spot prices), attackers can inflate collateral value using flash loans.

Flash Loan Attacks

Flash loans allow attackers to temporarily control large amounts of capital and manipulate markets.

Incorrect Collateral Factors

Improper risk parameters can cause systemic insolvency.

Accounting Bugs

Errors in interest calculation or balance updates may allow borrowers to drain the protocol.

